%md
## Introduction
PGX is a part of the supported Oracle Property Graph releases included in Oracle Database and Oracle Big Data Spatial and Graph.
The Customer 360 sample data is an integrated dataset of 1) accounts and account owners, 2) purchases by the people who own those accounts, and 3) transactions between these accounts. The combined dataset is then used to perform the following common graph query and analyses: pattern matching, detection of cycles, finding important nodes, community detection, and recommendation.

msg.data:
Introduction

PGX is a part of the supported Oracle Property Graph releases included in Oracle Database and Oracle Big Data Spatial and Graph.
The Customer 360 sample data is an integrated dataset of 1) accounts and account owners, 2) purchases by the people who own those accounts, and 3) transactions between these accounts. The combined dataset is then used to perform the following common graph query and analyses: pattern matching, detection of cycles, finding important nodes, community detection, and recommendation.

g = session.getGraph("Customer 360")

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Pattern Matching
Find accounts that had an inbound and an outbound transfer, of over 500, on the same day. The PGQL query for this is:

msg.data:
Pattern Matching

Find accounts that had an inbound and an outbound transfer, of over 500, on the same day. The PGQL query for this is:

paragraphs.text:
%pgx
// Show account which has inbound transfer and outbound transfer on the same day and their amount are both more than 500.
g.queryPgql("""
  SELECT a.account_no, a.balance, t1.amount, t2.amount, t1.date
  MATCH (a)<-[t1:transfer]-(a1)
      , (a)-[t2:transfer]->(a2)
  WHERE t1.date = t2.date
    AND t1.amount > 500
    AND t2.amount > 500
    AND a.balance < 300
""");

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Detect Cycles
Next we use PGQL to find a series of transfers that start and end at the same account such as A to B to A, or A to B to C to A.

msg.data:
Detect Cycles

Next we use PGQL to find a series of transfers that start and end at the same account such as A to B to A, or A to B to C to A.

paragraphs.text:
%pgx
// Show any transactions where money is going back and forward in two accounts.
g.queryPgql("""
  SELECT a1.account_no, t1.date, t1.amount, a2.account_no, t2.date, t2.amount
  MATCH (a1)-[t1:transfer]->(a2)-[t2:transfer]->(a1)
  WHERE t1.date < t2.date
""");

%pgx
// Show any cyclic transactions in three accounts.
g.queryPgql("""
  SELECT a1.account_no, t1.amount, a2.account_no, t2.amount
       , a3.account_no, t3.amount
  MATCH (a1)-[t1:transfer]->(a2)-[t2:transfer]->(a3)-[t3:transfer]->(a1)
  WHERE t1.date < t2.date
  AND t2.date < t3.date
""");

%pgx
cs = sg.createChangeSet()
rs = sg.queryPgql("SELECT DISTINCT a WHERE (a)-[:transfer]-()")
for (r in rs) {
  v = r.getVertex(1)
  i = result.getPartitionIndexOfVertex(v)
  cs.updateVertex(v.getId()).setProperty("component", i)
}
sg = cs.build()

%pgx
sg.queryPgql("""
  SELECT a.component, COUNT(a.account_no), MAX(a.account_no)
  MATCH (a)
  GROUP BY a.component
  ORDER BY a.component
""")

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Recommendation

%pgx
sg = g.filter(new EdgeFilter("edge.label()='purchased'"))

%pgx
CS = sg.createChangeSet()
RS = sg.queryPgql("SELECT a, x WHERE (a)-[:purchased]->(x)")
i = 1
for (r in RS) {
    a = r.getVertex(1).getId()
    x = r.getVertex(2).getId()
    CS.addEdge(x, a).setLabel("purchased_by")
    i++
}
sg = CS.build()
sg.queryPgql("""
  SELECT ID(r), a.account_no, x.name
  MATCH (a)<-[r:purchased_by]-(x)
""")

%pgx
vertexSet = sg.createVertexSet()
vertexSet.addAll(201)
analyst.personalizedPagerank(sg, vertexSet)

%pgx
sg.queryPgql("""
  SELECT ID(x), x.name, x.pagerank
  MATCH (x)
  WHERE x.type = 'merchant'
    AND NOT EXISTS (
      SELECT *
      MATCH (x)-[:purchased_by]->(a)
      WHERE ID(a) = 201
    )
  ORDER BY x.pagerank DESC
""")
